Question: Changes printed to a file aren't being saved: :try{ private fileWriter= new PrintWriter(new FileWriter(file.txt));                fileWriter.print("hello world");                System.out.println("file written");                fileWriter.close();}catch (IOException e){            e.printStackTrace();        } finally {        }I have this text file in my source folder. So far, there haven't been any errors with accessing it. However, when I close the program or after when the files should have been written when I open the text file I don't find them there, however I did check the bin folder ocne and it seemed to print hello world to the temp copy there. I want the changes it makes to be permanent.
Please using this api: PrintWriter.write.
Answer:<<<api>>>: PrintWriter.write
<<<code>>>: try { fileWriter = new PrintWriter(new FileWriter(file.txt)); fileWriter.println("hello world"); fileWriter.close(); } catch (IOException e) { e.printStackTrace(); }
<<<explanation>>>: The PrintWriter.println method writes a line terminator after the string. This is what you need to ensure that your changes are saved permanently.

A: The issue is that you are not writing a line terminator after each line. In the PrintWriter.write method, you are only writing the characters "1", "2", and "3" without a line terminator. The BufferedReader.readLine method waits for a line terminator (which is '\n' or '\r\n' depending on the system) to read a line. Since you are not providing one, it reads until it encounters the end of the stream.
You should use PrintWriter.println instead of PrintWriter.write to write each line followed by a line terminator.
Here is the corrected code:
PrintWriter printWriter = ...
printWriter.println("1");
printWriter.println("2");
printWriter.println("3");


